	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Sharp fall in world cereals production forecast</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 August 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The US Department of Agriculture has made the largest downward revision (12%) to its estimate for a maize crop&nbsp;in a quarter of a century which, with a 37% cut in its estimate for the end-of-season inventory, contributed to rises in prices (for delivery in December 2012) of 44% for maize, 45% for wheat and 17% for soya beans. According to the <i>Financial Times</i>, the USA accounts ‘for one in every three tonnes of the staple grains traded on the global market.’ The article asks whether it is correct to draw ‘comparisons with 2007-08, when a price surge triggered a wave of food riots in more than 30 countries from Bangladesh to Haiti, and 2010, when Russia banned grain exports, setting off a price jump that some have argued helped to cause unrest across the Arab world last year.’</p><p>The answer is ‘not yet’, not least because the rice producing states have not experienced the same adverse weather as the wheat/maize producers. It is stocks of maize and soya beans that are particularly tight; the situation on wheat and rice – staple foods in many developing countries – is less severe. The price at which rice is trading is over 40% below its 2008 high.</p><p>Even if the outlook for other major cereal suppliers remains unchanged, however, there could be an indirect effect on the agricultural sector and overall economy of ACP states (as well as other countries) through the impact on the global economy. With the outlook for global recovery looking increasingly brittle, the inflationary effect of higher prices for some cereals may restrict the scope for major economies to boost growth. This could, in turn, impact on the agricultural exports of ACP states as well as other developing countries.</p><p>The news comes only a week after the FAO reported that its food price index had fallen for the third consecutive month. Although the general easing of world supply relative to demand this year has reduced some of the pressure on stocks, levels in some cereals remain tight. Global maize stocks are forecast by USDA to fall to just 15% of annual demand, close to a record low. The capacity of the global cereal market to cope with any further ‘bad news’ may thus be limited.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA ‘World agricultural supply and demand estimates’, WASDE 508, 11 July 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.usda.gov/oce/commodity/wasde/latest.pdf" target="_self">http://www.usda.gov/oce/commodity/wasde/latest.pdf</a></p><p><i>Financial Times</i>, ‘US slashes corn production forecast’, 11 July 2102</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/7bd4791e-cb50-11e1-916f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz20zGmTzCX" target="_self">http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/7bd4791e-cb50-11e1-916f-00144feabdc0.html#axzz...</a></p><p><i>Financial Times</i>, ‘Food crisis fears as US corn soars’, 13 July 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/ad1ec426-cd07-11e1-92c1-00144feabdc0.html#axzz20zGmTzCX" target="_self">http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/ad1ec426-cd07-11e1-92c1-00144feabdc0.html#axzz...</a></p><p>FAO, ‘FAO food price index falls again’, 5 July 20125</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/150904/icode/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/150904/icode/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>For ACP agricultural trade there are lessons to be learned at several levels from the news of the effects on global production of the US heatwave. One is to note the rapid speed at which forecasts of a surplus of supply over demand have been reversed. There has been a lot of work on whether the world cereal market has become significantly more volatile, some of which was summarised in the Inter-Agency Report for the G20 a year ago (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/General/G20-task-force-recommends-wide-ranging-action-to-reduce-impact-of-world-price-volatility" target="_blank">G20 task force recommends wide-ranging action to reduce impact of world...</a>’, 5 July 2011). While the verdict was not clear a year ago, each new episode of a rapid shift from plenty to scarcity (and back again) increases the evidence that volatility has increased.</p><p>A second lesson is that whereas the recent concern over increased volatility has focused on the role of financial flows, this time around the immediate cause of the problem is clearly ‘fundamentals’; the US crop has been very badly hit. The source of any increased volatility is important as the appropriate responses differ. To the extent that the problem is an actual shortage of supply relative to demand, it is global stocks that offer a solution. These are much lower than they were in earlier decades. This is in part linked to policy changes in major OECD producers (e.g. the EU’s move away from price support and intervention buying to farmer income support programmes). However the new cycle of price volatility linked to market fundamentals may add further weight to calls that global stock holdings be increased.</p><p>The third, and most immediate, lesson is that there could be competition for food supplies from the world market in the coming year. If ACP countries that are normally exporters to their region impose export controls in 2012/3, as some did in 2010/11, it will put further strain on regional integration. It will reinforce the wariness of net deficit states about relying on their neighbours when the going gets tough. To avoid this, and safeguard the legitimate interests of both net importer and net exporters, requires prior consultation and contingency planning. If it sends a warning shot that regional partners need to begin this process, the historic revision of USDA crop estimates may have served a good purpose.</p>
		</div>
		
